{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed — unchanged files are not scanned.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure mode is at a module boundary: changed-file selection must be handed correctly into the analyzer. A pure unit test of filtering logic is too narrow, but real OS/network behavior is not required by the behavior text itself. I considered System because PR file lists often come from GitHub APIs, but rejected it since this behavior does not require validating real HTTP/Actions runtime semantics.","test_description":"Wire PR-change discovery output (fixture with changed + unchanged files) into the analysis pipeline and assert only changed paths are passed to rule execution; verify unchanged files are never analyzed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Findings are grouped by severity (error, warning, info) in the posted PR comment.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Grouping correctness depends on interaction between findings aggregation and comment rendering/post payload construction. Unit tests can validate grouping logic alone, but the real failure boundary here is the handoff into comment content generation. I considered System due to real GitHub comment posting, but rejected it because the behavior text is about grouping structure, not real API transport behavior.","test_description":"Run pipeline components from collected findings through comment builder and posting adapter (stubbed transport), then assert output comment sections are correctly grouped and labeled as error/warning/info.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A pull request that touches 200 files completes analysis within the 10-minute Actions timeout.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is explicitly about CI runtime under GitHub Actions timeout constraints, which is a real environment/performance boundary. In-process mocks can hide scheduling, subprocess, and I/O costs that determine timeout behavior.","test_description":"Execute the lint step in an Actions-like system environment (or actual GitHub Action run) against a 200-file PR-sized fixture and assert end-to-end completion under 10 minutes wall-clock.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the linter process crashes on a malformed file, the remaining files are still analyzed and results posted.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The behavior names a linter process crash, which is real subprocess failure semantics (exit/crash) rather than just in-process exception logic. Mocking process behavior can miss real crash-handling and continuation behavior.","test_description":"Run the pipeline with the real linter subprocess on a corpus containing one crash-triggering malformed file plus valid files; assert the step continues analyzing remaining files and still posts aggregated results.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate findings on the same line from overlapping rules are deduplicated in the output.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure typically appears when outputs from multiple rule modules are merged and then rendered, so module interaction matters. I considered Unit for a pure dedup function, but rejected it because the behavior explicitly involves overlapping rules feeding output, i.e., cross-module aggregation context.","test_description":"Feed findings from multiple rule modules with intentional same-file/same-line duplicates through aggregation + output generation, then assert only one finding per dedup key appears in final output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
